The author, or rather the authors, of this Chronicle cannot now be ascertained. It has hitherto been customary to ascribe its commencement to an abbot of Duudreuan in Galloway, but this is one of the errors into which the faulty transcript perpe- tuated by the edition of 1684 has led all subsequent writers* The true reading of the memorandum upon which it is founded is as follows :—“ Memorandum, quod abbas de Duudraynand mutuavit cronica de Melrose, iu quibus suerunt xiiij. quaterni, folio vxx et xix.”† At a subsequent period the abbot procured the loan of the remaining portion, “ Abbas de Duudrainan mutuo accepit reliquam partem cronicorum istorum.”‡ In the first of these quotations the word mutuavit has been mistaken for inchoavit, and hence the origin of that claim upon our gratitude hitherto exercised by the abbot of Duudreuan. In this, as in other investigations of a similar nature, it is much easier to produce negative than positive testimony; aud having removed the abbot of Duudreuan from hia eminence, the Editor must confess that he is unable to place any other claimant in his stead.
